1
00:00:00,605 --> 00:00:27,269
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa

2
00:00:28,887 --> 00:00:40,783
Homage to the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:40,804 --> 00:00:48,954
During the summer I got interested in a teaching commonly known as Transcendent Dependent Arising, the Upanishads Sutta.

4
00:00:49,845 --> 00:00:59,579
I was drawn to this via the six maxims, ethical practices designed to help us face climate change in a way that preserves our integrity.

5
00:01:00,720 --> 00:01:08,131
One of these maxims is to see our good fortune in being alive right now at a time of such crisis for mankind.

6
00:01:09,692 --> 00:01:14,739
Instead of seeing floods, droughts, wildfires, soil erosion as horrors,

7
00:01:15,343 --> 00:01:24,257
We are to welcome each one as an opportunity to develop courage, resilience, and other gifts that come of meeting suffering with open arms.

8
00:01:25,959 --> 00:01:35,111
Dukhanita Isa Sutta provides Dhamma support for this, as it traces out the list of causes and conditions leading to enlightenment.

9
00:01:36,593 --> 00:01:40,980
The first 12 steps might be familiar, showing how we create dukkha,

10
00:01:41,668 --> 00:01:49,456
meaning suffering in all its variations from minor irritation to heartbreak, excruciating pain or abject fear.

11
00:01:50,658 --> 00:01:57,825
By believing we can make ourselves happy in a world which is unstable, uncontrollable, inherently unsatisfying.

12
00:01:58,986 --> 00:02:07,575
What is special about this teaching is that it doesn't stop at dukkha, but traces an equal number of steps leading from dukkha to liberation.

13
00:02:09,007 --> 00:02:14,895
It gives us a list of skills and qualities we can and should develop to bring about our own liberation.

14
00:02:16,737 --> 00:02:33,842
I've recently attended a tricycle online course entitled The Spiral to Freedom, in which the teachers, John Peacock and Akinchino Weber, look at this particular teaching, as well as a number of related teachings which explore the same area.

15
00:02:35,344 --> 00:02:37,848
They refer to these as the spiral teachings,

16
00:02:38,385 --> 00:02:42,472
and call the path leading dukkha to liberation a spiral path.

17
00:02:43,454 --> 00:02:49,203
They also stress that all the links in the spiral path can be seen in ordinary daily life.

18
00:02:51,025 --> 00:02:54,150
It all starts with dukkha, which I think is really good news.

19
00:02:55,431 --> 00:03:02,802
If you know you're unhappy, irritated, out of sorts, then you're already at the launching pad for the spiral path.

20
00:03:03,824 --> 00:03:05,187
Taking dukkha as a given

21
00:03:05,572 --> 00:03:13,302
The teachings suggest another number of responses, which John and Akinchino refer to as entry points to the spiral.

22
00:03:15,284 --> 00:03:18,349
Let's take the Duke of Climate Change as an example.

23
00:03:19,371 --> 00:03:22,776
Suppose we are in a stew of misery at news of another wildfire.

24
00:03:23,757 --> 00:03:25,680
How can we meet this with open arms?

25
00:03:27,181 --> 00:03:31,527
For some, faith is the easiest way to counter the pull into negative thinking.

26
00:03:32,609 --> 00:03:34,752
This could be the bright faith of the beginner,

27
00:03:35,018 --> 00:03:37,721
or the mature trust that grows with long practice.

28
00:03:39,383 --> 00:03:48,655
Every time another dark thought takes us back into the pit, we place our trust in the Dhamma to draw ourselves out.

29
00:03:51,438 --> 00:03:55,824
It could help to look at a Buddha Rupa or whatever symbolises the Dhamma for you.

30
00:03:57,526 --> 00:04:02,532
Buddha touched the earth when he needed all his faith, and this is worth trying out sometime.

31
00:04:03,133 --> 00:04:04,435
Place your hands on the ground

32
00:04:04,668 --> 00:04:09,756
feel its stability, its solidity, trust the vastness of the earth as a grounding in truth.

33
00:04:10,937 --> 00:04:13,300
For some of us, faith might not come so easily.

34
00:04:14,223 --> 00:04:21,413
News of an environmental catastrophe and knowing that this has been wrought by human greed stimulates doubt rather than faith.

35
00:04:22,314 --> 00:04:26,040
And we are flooded by questions like, what is life all about?

36
00:04:27,122 --> 00:04:29,045
But the only answer is, I don't know.

37
00:04:29,065 --> 00:04:33,072
If we're willing to explore the experience of I don't know,

38
00:04:33,338 --> 00:04:38,204
This is wise investigation, a second entry point to the spiral.

39
00:04:39,725 --> 00:04:44,793
Although we don't have the answers, we have access to teachings that can point us in the right direction.

40
00:04:46,154 --> 00:04:53,665
Thus, the feeling of bewilderment is the catalyst that motivates us to learn about suffering and how it can be transcended.

41
00:04:53,704 --> 00:04:59,192
At other times, investigation may seem irrelevant.

42
00:04:59,672 --> 00:05:03,177
We want to do something, anything to relieve the suffering.

43
00:05:04,473 --> 00:05:08,838
In this case, virtue becomes the link from duca to the spiral.

44
00:05:09,980 --> 00:05:13,204
We respond to the news of the wildfire with ethical action.

45
00:05:14,064 --> 00:05:21,233
We might donate to a charity supporting those affected, sign a petition or write to our local council.

46
00:05:22,355 --> 00:05:26,119
We find some positive action aiming to minimise the harm and pain.

47
00:05:27,620 --> 00:05:32,387
As well as being beneficial for the world, this counters the pull into depression.

48
00:05:32,704 --> 00:05:38,153
owing to the perilous state of the world, restores our confidence in the power of goodness.

49
00:05:40,396 --> 00:05:46,867
But sometimes we just can't find the energy, the goodwill need to sign yet another petition or make that donation.

50
00:05:48,189 --> 00:05:52,014
Everything in us wants to turn away from the world, forget all its horrors.

51
00:05:53,096 --> 00:05:58,964
This impulse contains the wisdom of restraint, which is another entry point to the spiral

52
00:06:00,564 --> 00:06:08,435
We let ourselves turn away from activity, withdraw to some quiet place, let go of all the thoughts about climate change or other news.

53
00:06:09,617 --> 00:06:13,302
Give ourselves the silence and rest we need to let our hearts heal.

54
00:06:13,343 --> 00:06:21,394
This could mean an hour's meditation, it could mean a long retreat, or perhaps all we can do is a few mindful breaths.

55
00:06:22,235 --> 00:06:23,557
Whatever works is fine.

56
00:06:23,918 --> 00:06:26,521
We're honouring a wholesome response to dukkha.

57
00:06:29,067 --> 00:06:30,468
The opposite can happen too.

58
00:06:30,870 --> 00:06:33,473
The news of the wildfire leads to restlessness.

59
00:06:34,274 --> 00:06:37,540
We can't keep still and we certainly don't want to turn inwards.

60
00:06:38,702 --> 00:06:40,786
Instead, we need something to occupy us.

61
00:06:41,206 --> 00:06:44,651
In this case, we can use the entry point of dedication.

62
00:06:46,134 --> 00:06:49,139
We could wash the dishes as if this were a sacred ceremony.

63
00:06:50,201 --> 00:06:54,889
The most important task in the world, taking care of all the little details.

64
00:06:56,168 --> 00:07:00,052
Although we can't fix the wildfire, we can take care of what is at hand.

65
00:07:00,733 --> 00:07:04,379
And this is a very worthy response to Duca.

66
00:07:06,601 --> 00:07:12,971
At other times, the thought of taking care of anyone or anything seems an impossible burden.

67
00:07:12,990 --> 00:07:19,059
Perhaps thoughts of who is to blame and how it should be fixed crash into one another, making our heads spin.

68
00:07:20,401 --> 00:07:24,065
In this case, mindfulness provides a good entry point to the spiral.

69
00:07:25,278 --> 00:07:28,521
We don't have to follow each sensation of the breath.

70
00:07:28,541 --> 00:07:36,591
We can use phrases like walking to the shops, making the dinner, driving to work to keep us present, alert, mindful.

71
00:07:37,913 --> 00:07:47,444
Although news of the wildfire might still be tempting us to fret and worry, we are choosing present reality as an antidote to those dead ends.

72
00:07:48,285 --> 00:07:52,990
And this is a valid way to lift ourselves out of dukkha and into the spiral path.

73
00:07:55,045 --> 00:07:58,189
Sometimes we can't even muster the energy to be mindful.

74
00:07:58,709 --> 00:08:00,012
Everything seems hopeless.

75
00:08:00,653 --> 00:08:03,057
In this case, we need to look outside ourselves.

76
00:08:04,098 --> 00:08:08,004
Let inspiration become our stepping stone from dukkha to the spiral.

77
00:08:09,567 --> 00:08:12,069
Who or what will draw attention away from misery?

78
00:08:12,571 --> 00:08:14,413
Persuade us that life is worth living.

79
00:08:15,995 --> 00:08:17,598
For some, it's a weekend camping.

80
00:08:17,959 --> 00:08:20,062
Others might sign up for a study course.

81
00:08:20,802 --> 00:08:24,528
It could be as simple as meeting a friend, listening to a dhamma talk,

82
00:08:24,930 --> 00:08:27,112
leafing through photos of happier times.

83
00:08:28,774 --> 00:08:34,058
I keep some well-worn biographies at hand when I need a lift or go out for a long walk.

84
00:08:35,399 --> 00:08:41,265
Sometimes gazing at the sunset is enough to inspire me, remind me of life's progress.

85
00:08:44,948 --> 00:08:49,613
Thus, we have seven options for digging ourselves out of Duggan and into the spiral.

86
00:08:50,634 --> 00:08:54,717
Faith, investigation, virtue, restraint,

87
00:08:55,102 --> 00:08:58,307
dedication, mindfulness, inspiration.

88
00:09:00,450 --> 00:09:09,981
Each of us will have our own strengths, our preferred entry points, and it will also vary from one situation to another and depending on what mood we're in.

89
00:09:11,203 --> 00:09:14,167
Working with these entry points is a powerful practice.

90
00:09:15,188 --> 00:09:20,975
As we try these in practical situations, we get to know our strengths, learn to play to them.

91
00:09:22,812 --> 00:09:31,124
This provides a contrast with the standard Vipassana approach, where we simply observe, don't interfere, don't try to make things better.

92
00:09:32,986 --> 00:09:41,940
To launch ourselves out of dukkha and into the spiral path, we're allowed to be biased, seek out and amplify feelings and mind states that lift us up.

93
00:09:43,783 --> 00:09:50,052
Mindfulness is not only an entry point in itself, but it's also working in the background for all entry points.

94
00:09:50,756 --> 00:09:57,525
noticing what works, what doesn't, when we've gone too far, when we need to step back, take it easy.

95
00:09:58,667 --> 00:10:00,428
Try another approach when we're ready.

96
00:10:02,091 --> 00:10:06,136
Once we've found an entry point, the next link in the spiral is gladness.

97
00:10:07,437 --> 00:10:11,462
A moment ago we were stuck in the pits of dukkha, now we've found a way forward.

98
00:10:12,423 --> 00:10:15,128
The heart quite naturally gladdens when this happens.

99
00:10:16,870 --> 00:10:19,953
Surprisingly, the feeling of gladness is easily overlooked.

100
00:10:20,542 --> 00:10:28,956
We can be so intent on doing our virtuous action, so immersed in the beauty of the sunset, that we don't notice the change of heart.

101
00:10:30,457 --> 00:10:39,933
Unless we pay attention to this, we could inadvertently start another round of dukkha, stressing ourselves out in the effort to do our good deeds.

102
00:10:41,134 --> 00:10:45,182
So inspired by the sunset that the rest of life pales by comparison.

103
00:10:47,322 --> 00:10:54,211
We need to be on the lookout for gladness to deepen our faith that there is really a path leading from suffering to liberation.

104
00:10:55,033 --> 00:10:57,136
And it is possible for me to follow this.

105
00:10:58,778 --> 00:11:01,923
My advice also would be not to expect too much.

106
00:11:02,825 --> 00:11:08,833
A tiny glimpse of gladness is all the evidence we need that there is something here worth cultivating.

107
00:11:10,616 --> 00:11:16,164
Gladness sets up the necessary conditions for rapture, the next link in the spiral

108
00:11:17,748 --> 00:11:26,461
The word suggests an over-the-top joy, but if we are on the lookout for it, we find rapture to be quite a simple, down-to-earth experience.

109
00:11:28,063 --> 00:11:34,914
The background mood of gladness helps us engage, be interested in whatever we experience.

110
00:11:34,934 --> 00:11:38,902
This engaged interest in present experience is what we mean by rapture.

111
00:11:40,344 --> 00:11:44,110
This can be experienced quite simply as interest or curiosity.

112
00:11:45,220 --> 00:11:47,883
Look out for this at the start of any activity.

113
00:11:48,803 --> 00:11:54,892
As you step into the shower, take the first bite of dinner, say hello to a friend, listen to a podcast.

114
00:11:56,273 --> 00:12:00,698
Sometimes it can feel a bit giddy or overexcited, expecting too much.

115
00:12:01,580 --> 00:12:05,945
Sometimes very mild, like a gentle uplift or refreshment.

116
00:12:08,408 --> 00:12:12,192
Rapture sets up the condition for the next link, tranquility.

117
00:12:13,293 --> 00:12:14,855
This was one I struggled with.

118
00:12:15,240 --> 00:12:23,408
Till Akinchino described tranquility as that cooling phase in every activity, when the initial fizz goes out of it.

119
00:12:24,389 --> 00:12:27,513
This put a completely different light on tranquility for me.

120
00:12:28,254 --> 00:12:44,049
And true enough, once I investigated that slight deflation and some new activity lost its sparkle, I detected an inner relaxation underlying the more obvious surface layer of disappointment.

121
00:12:45,227 --> 00:12:47,649
I needed to bring attention to the body for this.

122
00:12:47,691 --> 00:12:53,255
The mood of deflation still predominated in the mind.

123
00:12:54,417 --> 00:12:59,863
But within the tissues of the body, particularly the limbs, I sensed peace and ease.

124
00:13:01,024 --> 00:13:05,548
I realized that I had become more grounded, more settled within myself.

125
00:13:09,352 --> 00:13:14,457
So keep an eye out for any slight deflation when a new activity starts to feel humdrum.

126
00:13:16,091 --> 00:13:18,695
Ask whether deep down peace has descended.

127
00:13:19,676 --> 00:13:22,278
I never knew disappointment could hold such treasure.

128
00:13:23,500 --> 00:13:25,302
But don't go straight for tranquility.

129
00:13:25,783 --> 00:13:30,107
Skip over the rapture stage, thinking it's silly to be getting excited by things.

130
00:13:31,370 --> 00:13:38,898
For tranquility to have any depth, we need to put our heart into the activity, while it still strikes us as novel and interesting.

131
00:13:41,642 --> 00:13:43,803
The energy of enthusiasm lifts us up

132
00:13:44,458 --> 00:13:49,885
And that is the same energy which transforms to tranquility and the novelty wears off.

133
00:13:51,668 --> 00:13:55,852
Tranquility sets up the conditions needed for the next link, happiness.

134
00:13:57,313 --> 00:14:07,527
Once I had detected and assured myself that tranquility was really present, the mood of disappointment evaporated and instead the heart softened.

135
00:14:08,788 --> 00:14:11,091
I realised I was content, happy.

136
00:14:12,639 --> 00:14:22,048
While tranquility for me could be described as a bodily form of happiness, the recognition of tranquility allowed the happiness spread from body to mind.

137
00:14:23,809 --> 00:14:33,097
Unless I had looked for tranquility within that deflationary phase when the fizz went out of an activity, the mood of disappointment would have remained.

138
00:14:34,158 --> 00:14:42,647
Nothing had changed in my circumstances to make me happy, only that I'd noticed and paid attention to the physical relaxation,

139
00:14:42,998 --> 00:14:47,582
that happened as an activity turned from novel and exciting to humdrum.

140
00:14:49,705 --> 00:14:53,950
I hope any of you who often feel depressed will take this point to heart.

141
00:14:54,831 --> 00:15:01,878
Trust that it is possible to be happy, even if you can't change the circumstances of your life.

142
00:15:01,898 --> 00:15:08,806
But beware the temptation to skip over the early stages, early steps and go straight for tranquility or happiness.

143
00:15:09,907 --> 00:15:12,870
Each step needs the support of the previous ones.

144
00:15:13,761 --> 00:15:25,418
We need to investigate each one, be prepared to come back to Dukkha again and again, so as to get more familiar with the entry points, detect the change of heart to gladness and so on.

145
00:15:28,062 --> 00:15:36,916
A happy mind quite naturally rests attention on whatever it chooses to attend to, and thus happiness sets up the conditions needed for Samadhi.

146
00:15:38,477 --> 00:15:41,962
Samadhi is the ability of the mind to rest, be still,

147
00:15:42,836 --> 00:15:45,340
gather its energies around a particular focus.

148
00:15:46,721 --> 00:15:54,071
If we're happily washing the dishes, it won't take any effort to feel the rubbing movements, see the dishes, hear the gurgling of water.

149
00:15:55,371 --> 00:16:03,361
It's only when we're unhappy that we get distracted, planning or worrying so intently that we never notice our hands in contact with dishes.

150
00:16:04,663 --> 00:16:10,971
The unhappy mind has its energies going in multiple directions as one thought careers after another.

151
00:16:12,301 --> 00:16:13,822
The happy mind is unified.

152
00:16:14,344 --> 00:16:17,207
While washing dishes, we know we are washing dishes.

153
00:16:18,049 --> 00:16:20,732
The only thoughts that come up relate to washing dishes.

154
00:16:22,596 --> 00:16:24,619
There are many advantages to Samadhi.

155
00:16:25,480 --> 00:16:30,347
We sense the gathering of our usually scattered thoughts as restful healing.

156
00:16:31,389 --> 00:16:38,679
From the Buddha's point of view, the greatest value is that the gathered mind can see more deeply into whatever it focuses on.

157
00:16:40,481 --> 00:16:46,888
If we want to see the cause of suffering and the path to freedom, then Samadhi lets us see this more clearly.

158
00:16:50,312 --> 00:16:59,321
This brings us to the many fruits of the spiral path, which start with understanding the Dhamma and lead onwards to full liberation from all suffering.

159
00:17:00,361 --> 00:17:08,970
To stick with our climate change example, I might start with a confusing mix of anxiety, anger and despair at the news of the wildfire.

160
00:17:10,367 --> 00:17:18,198
If I can follow the spiral till the mind gathers in Samadhi, I might then see how I'm torturing myself with imagined fears.

161
00:17:19,278 --> 00:17:23,984
The horror has been grasped so tightly I feel guilty unless I'm suffering too.

162
00:17:25,326 --> 00:17:34,519
It comes as humbling relief to admit that I am not suffering physically and this liberates a much more genuine compassion for those who are.

163
00:17:36,457 --> 00:17:45,769
I hope you will try out these teachings, get to know your easiest entry points to the spiral and the transition from misery to gladness as you do this.

164
00:17:46,770 --> 00:17:47,692
A word of warning.

165
00:17:48,753 --> 00:17:54,821
Words like gladness, rapture, tranquility, happiness can set us up for disappointment.

166
00:17:56,324 --> 00:17:58,346
Set your expectations very low.

167
00:17:59,203 --> 00:18:02,326
A momentary uplift from dukkha counts as gladness.

168
00:18:03,107 --> 00:18:06,811
The slight buzz that comes from a new activity counts as rapture.

169
00:18:07,894 --> 00:18:14,000
The slight relaxation in the body when the buzz dies away counts as tranquility, and so on.

170
00:18:15,422 --> 00:18:17,243
Remember, small is beautiful.

171
00:18:18,625 --> 00:18:22,630
In small steps, may we all be liberated from suffering.

172
00:18:26,525 --> 00:18:27,628
Thanks so much.

173
00:18:28,652 --> 00:18:36,298
I just stopped recording now.

